const collectionKeys = [
    "default",
    "stations",
    "jpn",
    "terra",
    "mnml",
] as const;

export type ThemeCollectionKey = typeof collectionKeys[number];

/** Display metadata for a theme collection. */
interface ThemeCollectionMeta {
    key: ThemeCollectionKey;
    label: string;
}

/** Base theme metadata without computed properties — used for authoring theme entries. */
export type ThemeMetaBase = Omit<ThemeMeta, "label">;

/** Theme metadata including display name, appearance, and collection info. */
export interface ThemeMeta {
    /** Unique identifier for the theme. */
    key: ThemeKey;
    /** Short display name for the theme (e.g. "Dark", "Engineering", "Koyo Yoru"). */
    name: string;
    /** Full display label (e.g. "Black Atom — TERRA ∷ Fall Night"). */
    label: string;
    /** Appearance of the theme (light or dark). */
    appearance: "light" | "dark";
    /** Status of the theme (development, beta, or release). */
    status: "development" | "beta" | "release";
    /** Collection that the theme belongs to. */
    collection: ThemeCollectionMeta;
}

/** A complete theme definition with metadata, colors, UI tokens, and syntax colors. */
export interface ThemeDefinitionNext<TColor = Colordx> {
    meta: ThemeMeta;
    colors: {
        /** Primary color scale. */
        primaries: ThemePrimaryColorsNext<TColor>;
        /** 16-color terminal palette. */
        palette: ThemePaletteColorsNext<TColor>;
        /** UI color tokens split into background and foreground groups. */
        ui: ThemeUiColorsNext<TColor>;
        /** Syntax highlighting color tokens for all language constructs. */
        syntax: ThemeSyntaxColorsNext<TColor>;
    };
}

/** Map of all theme keys to their full definitions. */
export type ThemeKeyDefinitionMapNext<TColor = Colordx> = Record<
    ThemeKey,
    ThemeDefinitionNext<TColor>
>;

# Plan: Migrate color computation from culori → @colordx (#69)

## Goals

1. Replace `culori`-based color utilities (`oklch()`, `tint()`) with `@colordx/core` chainable color objects
2. Split feedback and git colors into dedicated nested properties on `ui`
3. Get the monitor app working end-to-end with one proof-of-concept theme before mass-migrating

## Scope

**This plan covers:** Phase 1 only — introducing `ThemeDefinitionNext` (colors-grouped, nested ui), building the `createThemeDefinition()` helper, and getting one "next" theme file rendering in the monitor alongside the legacy themes.

**Out of scope (future plans):**

- Fixing #70 (subprocess → dynamic import). That's an independent improvement.
- Mass-migrating the other ~50 themes to colordx
- Removing `culori` from deps
- Adapter templates: adapters opt in to themes via their own `black-atom-adapter.json`, so the new `-next` theme will not be auto-generated by any adapter. Adapter template updates for the nested shape happen in Phase 2/3.

## Strategy decision: introduce `ThemeDefinitionNext` with a `colors:` namespace

Two changes ride together:

1. **Structural — group colors under `colors:`.** `ThemeDefinitionNext` separates metadata from the color tree:

    ```ts
    interface ThemeDefinitionNext {
        meta: ThemeMeta;
        colors: {
            primaries: ThemePrimaryColors;
            palette: ThemePaletteColors;
            ui: ThemeUiColorsNext; // nested feedback / git
            syntax: ThemeSyntaxColors;
        };
    }
    ```

    This makes `walk()` cleaner — it traverses `input.colors` only, never crossing into `meta`. The `instanceof Colordx` leaf check stays (it differentiates Colordx from structural objects within the colors tree); meta is preserved verbatim by `createThemeDefinition` and not touched by `walk()`.

2. **`ui` shape — nested `feedback` / `git`.** `ThemeUiColorsNext` drops the legacy flat keys (`negative`, `warn`, `info`, `hint`, `positive`, `add`, `delete`, `modify`) in favor of `feedback: ThemeFeedbackColors` and `git: ThemeGitColors` on both `bg` and `fg`.

`ThemeDefinition` (legacy, top-level, flat ui) and `ThemeDefinitionNext` (colors-grouped, nested ui) coexist during transition. `themeMap` is typed `Record<ThemeKey, ThemeDefinition | ThemeDefinitionNext>`. Phase 2 migrates the 33 legacy themes to `ThemeDefinitionNext`. Phase 3 deletes the legacy type.

**Why two types instead of widening one?** Top-level vs. colors-grouped is a structural difference, not a per-key one — a single optional union would not narrow well in consumers and would defeat the readability win of the namespace. Two distinct types with a discriminated union (`"colors" in theme`) are cleaner.

**CSS variable contract is preserved.** `themeToCssVars` flattens from inside the colors subtree (`flatten(theme.colors)`), so paths produce the same CSS var names (`--ba-primaries-d10`, `--ba-ui-bg-default`, …). The `colors` segment is for TS code organization, not CSS.

## Context

Replace `culori` with `@colordx/core` for all color computation. The motivation:

- `colordx` returns chainable `Colordx` objects (`.darken(0.2)`, `.lighten(0.2)`, `.saturate(0.2)`) instead of our opaque `tint()` helper
- Split feedback and git colors into dedicated nested properties on `ui` (currently flat: `ui.bg.negative`, `ui.bg.add`, etc.)
- `HexColor` type simplified from `#${string}` to `string` (colordx `.toHex()` return type compatibility)

### Current state

Branch `69-migrate-color-computation-from-culori-to-colordx` already has:

- `@colordx/core@^5.4.3` in deps
- Parallel "raw" interfaces defined in `src/types/theme.ts` (`ThemeRawPrimaryColors`, `ThemeRawPaletteColors`, `ThemeCreatorOptionsNext`, `ThemeUiColorsNext`, `ThemeDefinitionNext`). **Note:** `ThemeUiColorsNext` and `ThemeDefinitionNext` will be reshaped in Phase 1.1 — the existing Colordx-bearing definitions become `ThemeUiColorsNextRaw` (input type), and the names `ThemeUiColorsNext` / `ThemeDefinitionNext` get re-pointed at the hex-output canonical Next shape.
- The existing `black-atom-terra-fall-day.ts` was partially refactored (now exporting `ThemeDefinitionNext` with live `Colordx` objects — breaks JSON serialization). **We will revert it back** to its pre-migration state and work with a new copy instead.
- `create-raw-palette-light.ts` and `create-ui-light-next.ts` (`Colordx`-based) created
- `deno.lock` updated
- `src/monitor-server.ts` has a `stderr: "inherit"` workaround that will be stashed for #70 — revert it.

### Monitor communication (for context)

```
Theme files → map.ts → monitor-dump-themes.ts (JSON.stringify)
  → subprocess stdout → monitor-server.ts (JSON.parse)
  → HTTP API :4171 → Vite proxy → React app
```

The subprocess exists solely to bypass Deno's module cache on file edits. Colordx objects can't survive `JSON.stringify` — they serialize as `{}`.

### Issue #70 (separate — stashed)

The subprocess+stdout IPC in monitor-server.ts is a known footgun, but it's an independent concern. It will be addressed in its own plan. For now:

- **`src/monitor-server.ts`**: revert the `stderr: "inherit"` workaround back to `stderr: "piped"`
- **`src/monitor-dump-themes.ts`**: keep as-is (will be deleted by #70 later)

---

## Approach

**Three phases, PoC-first.** Start with one theme (a new `-next.ts` file alongside the original), get the monitor working, verify visually, then convert the rest.

### Phase 1: Foundation — `ThemeDefinitionNext` + one "next" theme + monitor

Define the new types, build the helper, create the new-style theme file, register it, and get the monitor rendering it alongside legacy themes.

At the end of Phase 1:

- `ThemeDefinitionNext` exists as a separate type with `meta` + `colors: { primaries, palette, ui, syntax }`
- `ThemeUiColorsNext` carries nested `feedback` / `git` (no flat keys)
- A new `black-atom-terra-fall-day-next.ts` exports `ThemeDefinitionNext` (Colordx → hex converted by `createThemeDefinition`)
- `themeKeys`, `rawThemeKeyMetaMap`, and `map.ts` carry the new key
- `themeMap` is typed `Record<ThemeKey, ThemeDefinition | ThemeDefinitionNext>` — discriminated by `"colors" in theme`
- The old original `black-atom-terra-fall-day.ts` is reverted to its pre-migration state and continues to satisfy legacy `ThemeDefinition`
- The monitor shows both entries in the grid; the preview renders feedback/git tokens for the new theme via the css-vars compatibility shim

#### 1.1 Define `ThemeDefinitionNext` and `ThemeUiColorsNext`

In `src/types/theme.ts`:

- Define `ThemeGitColors` (`add` / `delete` / `modify` of `HexColor`) alongside the existing `ThemeFeedbackColors`.
- Replace the existing Colordx-bearing `ThemeUiColorsNext` with the **hex-output** shape used by the canonical Next definition:

    ```ts
    interface ThemeUiColorsNext {
        bg: {
            default: HexColor;
            panel: HexColor;
            float: HexColor;
            active: HexColor;
            disabled: HexColor;
            hover: HexColor;
            selection: HexColor;
            search: HexColor;
            contrast: HexColor;
            feedback: ThemeFeedbackColors;
            git: ThemeGitColors;
        };
        fg: {
            default: HexColor;
            subtle: HexColor;
            accent: HexColor;
            disabled: HexColor;
            contrast: HexColor;
            feedback: ThemeFeedbackColors;
            git: ThemeGitColors;
        };
    }
    ```

- Replace the existing `ThemeDefinitionNext` with the colors-grouped shape:

    ```ts
    interface ThemeDefinitionNext {
        meta: ThemeMeta;
        colors: {
            primaries: ThemePrimaryColors;
            palette: ThemePaletteColors;
            ui: ThemeUiColorsNext;
            syntax: ThemeSyntaxColors;
        };
    }
    ```

- Add `ThemeUiColorsNextRaw` (the Colordx-bearing twin of `ThemeUiColorsNext`) — input type for `createUiNext`. The current Colordx-bearing `ThemeUiColorsNext` becomes `ThemeUiColorsNextRaw` under this rename.
- Add `ThemeSyntaxColorsNextRaw` (Colordx mirror of `ThemeSyntaxColors`) — input type for `createSyntaxNext`.
- Update `ThemeKeyDefinitionMap`:

    ```ts
    type ThemeKeyDefinitionMap = Record<ThemeKey, ThemeDefinition | ThemeDefinitionNext>;
    ```

- Append `"black-atom-terra-fall-day-next"` to `themeKeys` (covered in 1.6).

The legacy `ThemeDefinition`, `ThemeUiColors`, `ThemeUiBackgroundColors`, and `ThemeUiForegroundColors` are NOT touched in Phase 1 — they remain the type for the 33 unchanged themes.

#### 1.2 Compatibility shim in `themeToCssVars`

The CSS var generator now needs to (a) read from `theme.colors` for new themes and (b) emit legacy flat aliases for the new nested shape until consumers are updated.

Update `monitor/src/lib/theme-css-vars.ts`:

```ts
export function themeToCssVars(theme: ThemeDefinition | ThemeDefinitionNext): Record<string, string> {
    if ("colors" in theme) {
        const vars = flatten(theme.colors);
        // Legacy flat aliases for transitional CSS — removed in Phase 2.2
        for (const scope of ["bg", "fg"] as const) {
            const feedback = theme.colors.ui[scope].feedback;
            const git = theme.colors.ui[scope].git;
            if (feedback) {
                vars[`--ba-ui-${scope}-negative`] = feedback.negative;
                vars[`--ba-ui-${scope}-warn`] = feedback.warning;
                vars[`--ba-ui-${scope}-info`] = feedback.info;
                vars[`--ba-ui-${scope}-positive`] = feedback.success;
            }
            if (git) {
                vars[`--ba-ui-${scope}-add`] = git.add;
                vars[`--ba-ui-${scope}-delete`] = git.delete;
                vars[`--ba-ui-${scope}-modify`] = git.modify;
            }
        }
        return vars;
    }
    const { meta: _, ...rest } = theme;
    return flatten(rest);
}
```

Notes:
- `hint` and the structural keys are not aliased — they have no nested counterpart.
- Path prefix is identical for both branches (`flatten` starts inside the color tree), so `--ba-ui-bg-default` etc. work for both legacy and new themes.
- The shim is single-purpose, time-bounded, and removed in Phase 2.2.

#### 1.3 Build `walk()` and `createThemeDefinition()` helper

Create `src/lib/create-theme-definition.ts`:

- Takes a theme-like object and a callback, applies the callback via a generic `walk()` helper
- `walk()` traverses every node (objects, arrays, primitives) and calls the callback in **post-order** (children first, then parent)
- The callback decides what to do with each value — `walk()` itself knows nothing about colors or `toHex`
- Callback is explicit so it can be swapped later for different output formats (union type)

**Treat `Colordx` as a leaf, not a walkable object.** `isWalkable()` MUST early-out on `instanceof Colordx` so traversal does not descend into Colordx internals. Without this, post-order would build a Colordx-shaped plain object (no prototype methods) and the parent callback would receive that — `toHex` would crash.

**Callback API: single object argument.** Drop the two-positional form; pass `{ node, path }` so future fields (e.g. `parent`, `key`) can be added without breaking callers.

**Typing strategy.** The callback transforms types (`Colordx → string`), so input type ≠ output type. Type the input as `unknown` / a generic walkable, type the return as `unknown`, and assert the final return type at the `createThemeDefinition` callsite. The earlier `WalkNode<T>` recursive type was abandoned — it produced a non-narrowing union and fought inference once transforms were introduced.

```ts
import { Colordx } from "@colordx";

type WalkKey = string | number | symbol;
type WalkPath = readonly WalkKey[];

interface WalkContext {
    node: unknown;
    path: WalkPath;
}

type WalkCallback = (ctx: WalkContext) => unknown;

function isWalkable(value: unknown): value is Record<PropertyKey, unknown> {
    if (typeof value !== "object" || value === null) return false;
    if (value instanceof Colordx) return false;
    if (value instanceof Date) return false;
    if (value instanceof RegExp) return false;
    return true;
}

export function walk(input: unknown, callback: WalkCallback): unknown {
    function visit(node: unknown, path: WalkPath): unknown {
        if (Array.isArray(node)) {
            const next = node.map((item, index) => visit(item, [...path, index]));
            return callback({ node: next, path });
        }

        if (isWalkable(node)) {
            const next: Record<PropertyKey, unknown> = {};
            for (const key of Reflect.ownKeys(node)) {
                next[key] = visit(node[key], [...path, key]);
            }
            return callback({ node: next, path });
        }

        return callback({ node, path });
    }

    return visit(input, []);
}
```

Usage in `createThemeDefinition`:

```ts
import { Colordx } from "@colordx";
import type { ThemeDefinitionNext, ThemeMeta } from "../types/theme.ts";

interface ThemeAuthoringInput {
    meta: ThemeMeta;
    colors: {
        primaries: ThemeRawPrimaryColors;
        palette: ThemeRawPaletteColors;
        ui: ThemeUiColorsNextRaw;          // Colordx-bearing nested shape
        syntax: ThemeSyntaxColorsNextRaw;  // Colordx-bearing
    };
}

export function createThemeDefinition(input: ThemeAuthoringInput): ThemeDefinitionNext {
    return {
        meta: input.meta,
        colors: walk(input.colors, ({ node }) => {
            if (node instanceof Colordx) return node.toHex();
            return node;
        }) as ThemeDefinitionNext["colors"],
    };
}
```

`walk()` only traverses `input.colors`; meta is preserved verbatim. Inside the colors subtree, every leaf is either a Colordx (converted) or a primitive (passed through). The `instanceof Colordx` check is what differentiates leaves from structural objects.

**Reuse:** `ThemeDefinitionNext` (return type) and the `ThemeRaw*` / `ThemeUiColorsNextRaw` / `ThemeSyntaxColorsNextRaw` interfaces (input shape) all defined in 1.1. `Colordx` type and class from `@colordx`.

**TDD approach:** Write tests first, implementing `walk()` incrementally — one behavior at a time (primitive passthrough → plain object recursion → array handling → Colordx-as-leaf conversion → nested mixed structures). See `dev-style-tdd` skill for the red-green-refactor loop.

#### 1.4 Revert terra-fall-day.ts to original state

Since we'll create a separate `-next.ts` file:

- Use git to restore `src/themes/terra/black-atom-terra-fall-day.ts` to its `main` state (`git checkout main -- src/themes/terra/black-atom-terra-fall-day.ts`)
- Confirm imports go back to `oklch` from `../../utils/color.ts`, `createFeedback`, `createUi` (flat-shape helper), and the export type is plain `ThemeDefinition`

#### 1.5 Create `black-atom-terra-fall-day-next.ts`

New file at `src/themes/terra/black-atom-terra-fall-day-next.ts`. See the template at the end of this Phase 1 section.

The new theme:

- Authors all colors as `Colordx` via `colordx("oklch(...)")`
- Builds `ui` via `createUiNext({ primaries, palette, feedback, git, accents })` — produces nested `feedback` / `git` Colordx objects under `bg` / `fg`
- Builds `syntax` via a NEW `createSyntaxNext({ primaries, palette, feedback })` — Colordx in, Colordx out (see 1.5a)
- Wraps the whole Colordx-bearing tree under `colors:` and passes it to `createThemeDefinition()`, which converts all Colordx leaves to hex via `walk()` in a single pass
- Returns a `ThemeDefinitionNext` with the **colors-grouped, nested feedback/git** shape

#### 1.5a Add `createSyntaxNext` for terra-light

To prove the whole Colordx → hex pipeline end-to-end, syntax goes through the same authoring → walk path as ui:

- Add `src/themes/terra/create-syntax-light-next.ts` — copy of `create-syntax-light.ts` but takes `ThemeCreatorOptionsNext` (Colordx inputs) and returns `ThemeSyntaxColorsNextRaw` (Colordx outputs). Body is identical — references `palette.blue`, `primaries.d20`, etc., which are already Colordx in the Next options.
- The other collections' syntax helpers stay untouched in Phase 1. Phase 3 introduces their `-next` variants during mass migration.

Note on git colors: the example values used in the WIP file (`add` = darkRed, `delete` = green) have swapped semantics. Treat the values in the template as placeholders — settle final git colors with Nik before sign-off.

#### 1.6 Register the new theme

The literal type `ThemeKey` is derived from `themeKeys`, and `themeKeyMetaMap` is keyed off it — so adding a theme requires THREE edits:

- `src/types/theme.ts` — append `"black-atom-terra-fall-day-next"` to `themeKeys`
- `src/types/themes.ts` — add a `rawThemeKeyMetaMap` entry under the TERRA collection block (status: `development`, name e.g. `"Fall Day Next"`, appearance `"light"`)
- `src/themes/map.ts` — import `blackAtomTerraFallDayNext` and add it under the TERRA section of `themeMap`

Adapter safety: `themeKeys` is consumed by `createAdapterConfigSchema` to validate per-adapter `black-atom-adapter.json` configs. Adding `-next` to `themeKeys` only makes it a _valid choice_ — no adapter will template it unless its config opts in. Confirmed safe.

#### 1.7 Update monitor consumers to handle the union

A handful of monitor consumers read `theme.ui` / `theme.palette` / `theme.primaries` / `theme.syntax` directly. With `themeMap` now a union, those need a small accessor:

```ts
// monitor/src/lib/get-colors.ts
export function getColors(theme: ThemeDefinition | ThemeDefinitionNext) {
    return "colors" in theme ? theme.colors : theme;
}
```

Update the call sites to read through `getColors(theme)`:

- `monitor/src/lib/theme-css-vars.ts` — handled in 1.2 (the discriminator already lives there)
- `monitor/src/routes/preview/ui.tsx`, `monitor/src/hooks/use-ui-preview.ts`, and any other place that destructures `{ palette, primaries, ui, syntax }` off `theme`

This is a mechanical, low-risk change — no rendering logic shifts, just the access path. Type-check catches every site.

#### 1.8 Verify monitor works

```bash
deno task dev
# → Monitor loads
# → "Terra Fall Day Next" appears in the theme grid alongside the original
# → Open preview → primaries/palette tokens render as hex
# → Open Tokens / Chrome / Form / Badges examples — feedback & git tokens render via the legacy --ba-ui-bg-* names emitted by the 1.2 shim
# → Original "Terra Fall Day" still renders correctly (unchanged)
# → deno check passes (legacy and Next themes both satisfy the union)
```

### Draft template: New theme definition structure

Below is the canonical structure for a "next" theme file. This is what every theme will look like after migration.

```ts
// src/themes/terra/black-atom-terra-fall-day-next.ts
import { colordx } from "@colordx";
import { createThemeDefinition } from "../../lib/create-theme-definition.ts";
import { themeKeyMetaMap } from "../../types/themes.ts";

